**13.3.3.1 Solving Quadratic Equations (Polynomial Equations of degree 2)**

**Useful result 4: Formula for solving quadratic equations**

Consider a degree 2 polynomial, i.e. the general quadratic equation \(az^{2}+bz+c=0\) where \(a,\,b,\,c\) can be real or complex.

Using the formula, \(z=\dfrac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^{2}-4ac}}{2a}\), we find that if the discriminant \(b^{2}-4ac<0\), the solutions are not real. Thus, we say that the roots of the given equations are complex (non-real).

In fact, the solutions of a quadratic equation with real coefficients will form a conjugate pair,

i.e. \(z=\dfrac{-b}{2a}+\dfrac{\sqrt{b^{2}-4ac}}{2a}\) or \(\dfrac{-b}{2a}-\dfrac{\sqrt{b^{2}-4ac}}{2a}\) (\(b^{2}-4ac<0\))

